Camp Elder. As Lurczysnki writes in his preface, the play contains no great atrocities: "The focus, rather, is on internal experiences and on depicting pained, sick, desparate, and resigned psyches, on depicting the methods by which people were turned into beasts, and beasts into freaks of nature." Available for the first time in English, The Old Guard is an important and compelling work of Holocaust literature that stands on a par with the work of Tadeusz Borowski and Primo Levi.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)vDrama. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xConcentration campsvDrama. 4aHistory : Holocaust Studies. 4aHistory : World War II. 4aLiterature : Drama. 7aHISTORY / Holocaust.2bisacsh1 aNitecki, Alicia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSpeca, Gerald W., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781438430836?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438430836423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438430836/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles